{ In this course, I will be taking you to through and offering recommendations against three of the most important systems in the '1.d4' complex. We'll be covering the Catalan, the 'London System' and the 'Jobava London'. As usual, I have tried to offer offbeat yet objectively sound ideas. This can be played against any opponent of any rating, as long as you're ready to play dynamic positions. Let's get started! }
1. d4
2... d5
3. c4
(4... Nf3 5. Nf6 6... c3 { This move order prevents us from playing ...c5 (White gets an extra option of playing dxc5) . Here, I recommend the rare } 7. a5 $5 {[%cal Gc8f5,Ge7e6,Rd1b3]} {  gaining space on the Queenside. White often intends to play Qb3 in these structures, which we meet by playing ...Ra7 & ...a4. The position remains complex with you taking your opponent out of the preparation on the 3rd move. Sounds like success to me! })
({ The London System. It is explored to death nowdays, but I still managed to came up with an idea that would help you catch most of your opponents off-guard. } 4... Bf4 5. Nf6 6... e3 ({ The 'Jobava London'. Here, I recommend playing } 7. Nc3 8... a6 9. e3 { and in this topical position, I propose playing the extremely rare } 10... h6 $5 { laying down a trap for them. Mind you, I do believe that ...h6 is perfectly sound and can even be played against Magnus! } 11. h4 { White often gains space on the Kingside in these lines and this what he had they would play. } (12... Nf3 { the computer recommends this but by playing Nf3, they have given up on their expansion plans with f3-g4. Black can comfortably play } 13. e6 {[%cal Gc7c5]} {  and prepare an expansion on the Queenside with ...c5. Black's play is easier than White's. }) 12... c5 13. dxc5 14... Nc6 15. Nf3 { This is white's idea against 4...c5 5.dxc5 (without ...h6-h4 included) . White often ends up being better there. However, in this case, the difference is that after } 16... Bg4 { they cannot play } 17. Be2 { due to the threat of } 18... Bxf3 19. Bxf3 20... e5 $17 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5]} {[%cal Gf8c5,Re5e4]} {  Black builds a massive center. White cannot play Bg5! This is why we had played ...h6! }) 7. c5 8... Nf3 { and in this topical position, I propose the rare } ({ the old main line with } 9. c3 10... Qb6 { is also covered in the course. Black remains on the better end of equality here. }) 9. Qb6 { intentionally delaying ...Nc6. The critical line goes with } 10... Nbd2 { where I recommend the almost unheard of move, } ({ moves like } 11. Nc3 { and }) (11. dxc5 { and }) (11. c4 { are also covered deeply in this course. }) 11. g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8]} {  we want to develop our bishop via g7. There are only 3 games that have ever been played in this line. We keep all pieces on the board and on move 5, your opponent's out of preparation! })
4... e6
5. Nf3
6... Nf6
7. g3 { The Catalan is one of the most solid openings that White players can employ. Here, I recommend an extremely tricky recommendation. }
8... Ne4 $5 { we want to convert to a Dutch Stonewall. And mind you, not the regular version of it, but with ...Be7!?. The idea is to keep options of playing ...h5-g5 alive! This is certainly not what you expect when you play the Catalan. The critical position arises after }
9. Bg2
10... Be7
11. O-O
12... f5 { and here, White has two major choices : 7.b3 & 7.Nc3. }
13. b3 { this is the most-played move in the position. However, this is precisely what Black was hoping for }
({ other moves like } 14... Nc3 { or })
(14... Qc2 { and })
(14... Nbd2 { and })
(14... Ne5 { are also covered in this course. We discuss the thematic plans as well as concrete moves in the theoretical part. These lines are extremely complex and thus it remains a perfect choice to play for a win while maintaining objective balance as Black! })
14... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} {[%cal Gc6d4]} {  increasing the tension in the center. We ask them to play Bb2. }
15. Bb2 { as soon as the bishop moves away from the c1-h6 diagonal, Black plays }
16... h5 $13 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gg7g5]} {  and looks to develop an initiative on the Kingside. The position is dynamically balanced though against unprepared opponents, Black has often obtained an advantage in the next 3 or 4 moves. I feel this is a perfect weapon to play a Catalan player because a) It takes them out of their comfort zone & b) It is fresh and objectively playable! }

