 { Welcome to the first chapter. We begin our coverage of the 'Catalan' with this chapter. }
1. d4 { t }
2... Nf6
3. c4
4... e6
5. Nf3
6... d5
7. g3 { The starting point of this chapter. White wants to play in the most ambitious way strategically by bringing their bishop onto g2, where it remains most active on the entire board. This a big theoretical tabiya and here, I recommend the extremely rare }
8... Ne4 $5 {[%cal Rf8e7,Rf7f5]} {  preparing to transpose to a 'Dutch' Stonewall with ...Be7 & ...f5 next. While the resulting positions to Dutch Stonewall aren't exactly unknown, this transposition to Dutch is hidden from all almost players who reach this position. This is an extremely ambitious attempt }
9. Bg2 { White continues with their intended plan. }
10... Be7 { we develop our bishop to e7, instead of the usual 'd6' square. The bishop is less actively placed here (as it doesn't control the e5-square) but in return, it helps prepare ...h5-h4 or ...g5 (as we'll soon see) . }
11. O-O { White's main move. They continuining developing normally. }
12... f5 { Black's point. We have transposed to the 'Dutch Stonewall'. This position can also arise via the following move order : 1.d4 e6 2.c4 f5 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.g3 d5 5.Bg2 Ne4!? 6.0-0 Be7. }
13. b3 { One of the two major moves. White wants to play Ba3 next. }
14... Nc6 {[%csl Rd4]} {[%cal Gc6d4]} {  instead of playing the usual ...c6, we bring our knight into the game to increase the pressure over the pawn on d4. }
15. Bb2 {[%cal Gb1d2,Rb1c3]} {  The most logical move. White changes their plans and decides to guard the d4-pawn with their bishop. Next, they want to play Nc3/Nbd2 and offer to trade a set of knights. }
(  { the critical } 16... Ba3 { is covered in the next chapter. } )
16... h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4]} {  this was the whole point behind ...Be7. Instead of playing passively, Black goes on a rampage on the Kingside. This line has been a favourite of GM Richard Rapport who has had amazing success with Black here. Black wants to open up the Kingside with ...h4 next. Unlike the slow Catalan positions, the position gets incredibly sharp here. }
17. Nc3 { White's main move. They bring in their knight to attack our knight on e4. }
(  { starting out with } 18... Nbd2 { t doesn't change anything. After } 19. h4 20... Nxe4 21. dxe4 { we transpose to the main line of this chapter. } )
(  { trying to stop the Kingside play with } 18... h4 $6 { t does more harm than good. It is now Black who can start blasting up the Kingside. } 19. g5 {[%cal Ge7h4]} {  This is why you need a bishop on e7! Black doesn't mind spoiling the pawn structure as long as the Kingside is open! } 20... hxg5 { What else? } 21. Bxg5 {[%cal Gh5h4]} {  we want to play ...h4 next. } 22... Nxg5 { White decides to eliminate our active bishop. } 23. Qxg5 { by eliminating our bishop, they also took away one of the defenders from around their king. } 24... Qc1 {[%csl Rg5]} {[%cal Gc1g5]} {  offering a trade of queens to reduce the pressure around their king. } 25. Qg7 {[%csl Rd4]} {[%cal Gg7d4,Gh5h4,Rc6d4]} {  we refuse the offer! We not only renew the threat of ...h4 but also threaten ...Nxd4. } 26... Qf4 { trying to prevent ...h4. } 27. h4 { we still offer the pawn nonetheless! } 28... gxh4 { White has managed to neutralise the pressure on the h-file but now the g-file's open! } 29. Bd7 $19 {[%csl Rg2]} {[%cal Ge8c8,Yc8g8,Rg8g2]} {  preparing ...0-0-0. The other rook will join the attack with ...Rdg8 next. Black keeps a decisive attack. All of this was played in: ½-½ (114) Gunina,V (2437) -Koneru,H (2554) Samarkand 2023. Although Koneru didn't manage to win, she had a winning position right out of the opening! } )
18... h4 { Black continues with their intended expansion on the Kingside. White has a few logical moves to choose from here. }
19. Rc1 $5 { This is what Stockfish recommends. This is what GM Lazavik & Spragett chose as well. White continues to ignore our threats and focuses on improving their pieces. The rook overprotects the c3 knight (thereby preventing ...Bb4) . White may also play cxd5-Ne5 in some lines now. }
( 20... Ne5 { t White wants to trade pieces to reduce the pressure in the position. I am not a big fan of this move though as the knight was an useful defender around White's king. } 21. Nxe5 22... dxe5 23. c6 {[%csl Rf2]} {[%cal Ge7c5,Gc5g1]} {  since the d4-pawn has moved to e5, Black also enjoys access to the open a7-g1 diagonal now! Any endgame is preferable for Black here as they keep more space while White has a set of doubled e-pawns. } 24... Nxe4 { here, it's important to be wise and play } 25. dxe4 { offering a trade of queens. } (  { playing } 26... fxe4 { was incorrect. After } 27. e3 {[%cal Gd1g4]} {  followed by Qg4, White is completely out of woods. } ) 26... Qxd8+ 27. Kxd8 $15 {[%cal Gd8c7]} {  Black remains better in the endgame thanks to the extra space they possess. } )
( 20... e3 { t This has been a popular response too. Here, I recommend } 21. hxg3 22... fxg3 23. Bb4 $132 {[%cal Gd8f6,Rf6h6]} {  Black not only exerts pressure on the c3-knight but also prepares a potential queen swing to the Kingside. The position remains complex but Black certainly has nothing to complain of here. } )
( 20... Nxe4 $6 { t trying to reduce one of the attackers. Not a big fan of this, as Black certainly doesn't mind trading the knights! } 21. dxe4 22... Ne5 23. Nxe5 24... dxe5 25. Bd7 $17 {[%cal Ge7c5,Rd8g5,Yd7c6]} {  all middlegames/endgames are better for Black due to their extra space. } )
20... Kf7 { instead of castling, I prefer keeping the rook on h8. The position remains incredibly complex but here's a sample line. }
21. e3 { White strengthens their center. }
22... hxg3
23. hxg3
24... Rh6 $132 {[%cal Gh6c6,Rf7g8,Re7b4,Yc8d7,Yd7e8,Ye8h5]} {  the rook is just better placed on the 6th rank. Black would want to tuck in their king to g8 next. After that, we may play ...Bd6/...Bb4 or improve our worst-placed piece, the c8-bishop, with ...Bd7-Be8 & ...Bh5. }

