( 11. Qxb2 12... Nbd2 { offers adequate compensation for White. } )
11. Qxd4 { the critical test. They offer a queen trade and play for a micro-pressure due to their lead in development. }
( 12... exd4 $5 { t can now be met with } 13. Qxb2 14... Nbd2 15. Bf5 { the difference here is that after } 16... cxd5 17. Nxd5 {[%csl Rf4]} {[%cal Gd5f4]} {  the bishop on f4 is attacked. A possible line is } 18... Nc4 19. Qc2 $11 { where White keeps just enough compensation to maintain the balance, but nothing more. } )
12... Nbd7 {[%csl Rb6]} {[%cal Gd7b6]} {  we ignore their threats and instead focus on our play. }
13. Qxb6 $5 { one of the two critical lines. }
( 14... Bg3 { t is too slow. After } 15. e6 $11 {[%cal Gf8c5]} {  Black has managed to solve all of their opening woes. } )
( 14... Nc3 { t White brings their knight out and gives us the chance to spoil their structure. } 15. Qxd4 16... exd4 17. dxc4 $1 { we take them up on their offer. } 18... Bxc4 ( 19. Nb5 { t also possible is } 20... Nd5 21. Bxc4 22... N7b6 23. Bb3 24... Bd7 $11 { Black keeps better pawn structure. Without the queens on the board, they have no attacking prospects. } ) 19. Nb6 { while White enjoys some initiative, Black has very easy play thanks to their spoiled structure. } 20... Bb3 ( 21. Bb5+ { t this is possible but after } 22... Bd7 23. Bxd7+ 24... Kxd7 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ge7e6,Gf8b4,Ra7a6]} {  these endings are trickier for White. Our king remains in do danger, while they have a big static weakness in the middle of the board. } ) 21. e6 22... O-O ( 23. Nb5 { t doesn't help them. After } 24... Bb4+ 25. Ke2 26... Nbd5 $11 { we equalise comfortably. } ) 23. Bb4 {[%cal Rb4c3,Rb6d5,Gc8d7]} {  if they give us a chance,we would love to spoil their pawn structure even further. Black keeps easy play here. } )
( 14... cxd5 { t } 15. Qxd4 16... Nxd4 17. Nxd5 $11 {[%cal Ge7e5]} {  Black might expand in the center with ...e5 next! } )
14... Nxb6
15. c5 { White gains space on the Queenside. This is the challenging response. }
( 16... Nbd2 { t allows us to liquidiate comfortably with } 17. e6 18... Rc1 19. dxc4 20... Nxc4 21. Bb4+ $11 { the resulting endings are quite comfortable for Black. } )
16... Na4
